    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section class="faq-sec">
      <h2>Melatonin Dosage — Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details class="fq"><summary>How much melatonin should an adult take?</summary><p>Start at 0.5-1mg, 30-60 minutes before bed. Research shows 0.3-1mg is often more effective than higher doses because it matches physiological melatonin levels. Maximum recommended: 5mg for most adults.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What is the best time to take melatonin?</summary><p>30-60 minutes before desired bedtime for sleep onset. 3-5 hours before current sleep time for circadian phase shifting. At destination bedtime for jet lag. Timing matters more than dose.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Can you take too much melatonin?</summary><p>Yes. Doses above 5mg rarely improve sleep and can cause grogginess, nightmares, headaches, and paradoxical insomnia. A meta-analysis found doses above 5mg no more effective than 1-3mg. More is not better.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>How much melatonin should elderly adults take?</summary><p>Start at 0.3-0.5mg, maximum 2mg. Elderly metabolize melatonin more slowly. Extended-release 2mg is FDA-approved in the EU for adults over 55 (Circadin). Check for drug interactions.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What melatonin dose is best for jet lag?</summary><p>0.5-3mg at destination bedtime for 3-5 nights after arrival. A Cochrane review confirmed effectiveness for flights crossing 5+ time zones. Higher doses showed no advantage over 0.5-3mg.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Should I take regular or extended-release melatonin?</summary><p>Immediate-release for falling asleep (sleep-onset insomnia). Extended-release for staying asleep (waking at 2-4 AM). Most gummy supplements are immediate-release.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Does melatonin interact with medications?</summary><p>Yes — blood thinners, diabetes meds, fluvoxamine (dramatically increases melatonin levels), immunosuppressants, blood pressure meds, and sedatives. Always inform your doctor about melatonin use.</p></details>
